			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2024</a> paper:</span><br><i>Method Bundles</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/DimiRacordon.html">Dimi Racordon</a>, <a href="../profile/DaveAbrahams.html">Dave Abrahams</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1145/3687997.3695633">10.1145/3687997.3695633</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t1a.html"><span class="tagM">T1A: Design</span></a><ul><li> It proposes a new language construct that bundles semantically related method variants under one name.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t3f.html"><span class="tagL">T3F: API</span></a><ul><li> The motivation is to improve API ergonomics by consolidating variant-heavy interfaces into coherent bundles.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t5f.html"><span class="tagL">T5F: Performance</span></a><ul><li> Bundling unlocks compiler optimizations by making relationships between variants explicit.
</li></ul></li></ul>
